The TP53 tumor suppressor gene is constitutively expressed in almost all cell types, and it acts as a transcription factor involved in a multitude of functions, including cell cycle control, programmed cell death, senescence, differentiation and development, DNA repair, and maintenance of genomic stability (reviewed in Hainaut and Hollstein
11
) As such, it is critically involved in oncogenesis, is the most frequently altered gene in human cancer, and has been implicated in the generation and progression of several types of brain tumors.*
